        content:
          "When both sides present competing frameworks, someone needs to provide the judge with meta-level criteria for choosing between them. This is called 'weighing' at the framework level, and it is one of the most overlooked skills in debate. Many debaters present their framework and argue substance under it, but never explain why the judge should prefer their framework over the opponent's. This leaves the judge to make the decision on their own, which is risky.\n\nThere are several meta-criteria judges commonly use. **Predictive power** asks which framework better predicts real-world outcomes — if adopting framework A leads to better policy decisions than framework B, that is a reason to prefer it. **Internal consistency** examines whether the framework contradicts itself — a framework that leads to logical paradoxes is less reliable. **Scope** considers which framework addresses more of the relevant concerns in the debate — a framework that can evaluate all the arguments on the flow is more useful than one that only addresses a subset.\n\nThe most effective debaters explicitly tell the judge how to choose between frameworks rather than simply asserting their own is correct. You might say something like: 'Even if you find both frameworks somewhat persuasive, prefer ours because it provides a clear decision calculus — you can weigh costs against benefits — while theirs gives you no mechanism for resolving competing claims.' This kind of meta-weighing gives judges a concrete reason to side with you on the framework question.",
