        content:
          "Hypothetical scenarios are a fundamental tool in debate, used to test the logical implications of an argument, expose weaknesses in an opponent's position, or illustrate abstract principles with concrete examples. When someone says 'Imagine a world where...' or 'What if we applied that logic to...', they are deploying a hypothetical. Mastering this technique is critical because hypotheticals can dramatically shift the direction of a debate.\n\nHypotheticals serve multiple functions. They can be used offensively to show that an opponent's reasoning leads to absurd conclusions (reductio ad absurdum). They can be used defensively to demonstrate that your principle holds even in extreme cases. And they can be used constructively to help the judge visualize the impact of a policy or position that has not yet been implemented. The versatility of hypotheticals makes them one of the most frequently used argumentative tools in competitive debate.\n\nHowever, hypotheticals are also among the most commonly misused tools. Poorly constructed hypotheticals can be easily dismissed as unrealistic, irrelevant, or misleading. This lesson teaches you how to construct hypotheticals that are persuasive and logically rigorous, and how to respond effectively when your opponent uses hypotheticals against you.",
