          "**Policy Debate**\nIn policy debate, hypotheticals often take the form of impact scenarios — projections about what will happen if a policy is or is not adopted. The key to effective policy hypotheticals is grounding them in evidence. Rather than speculating wildly about consequences, use expert analyses, historical parallels, and data-driven projections. A hypothetical about economic collapse is far more persuasive when backed by an economist's warning than when presented as pure speculation.\n\n**Value Debate (Lincoln-Douglas)**\nIn LD debate, hypotheticals are used primarily to test value hierarchies and philosophical principles. Thought experiments are especially common and effective here. When debating whether justice requires equality, for instance, you might construct a scenario where perfect equality leads to universal mediocrity to test whether equality is truly the highest value. The philosophical tradition provides a rich library of thought experiments you can adapt.\n\n**Parliamentary and Public Forum**\nIn formats that prioritize accessibility, hypotheticals should be intuitive and relatable. Avoid overly abstract philosophical scenarios and instead use examples the judge can immediately understand. 'Imagine you are a small business owner who...' is more effective in these formats than 'Consider a Rawlsian original position in which...' The goal is to make the hypothetical feel real and immediate to a lay judge.\n\n**Cross-Examination**\nHypotheticals are devastatingly effective in cross-examination because they force your opponent to commit to a position in real time. Ask a series of hypothetical questions that gradually escalate, leading your opponent toward an uncomfortable conclusion. The key is to plan your question sequence in advance so that each question logically follows from the previous answer.",
