        content:
          "Most debates operate within an ethical framework — debaters argue about what is right or wrong, just or unjust, beneficial or harmful. But meta-ethics goes a level deeper: it asks questions about ethics itself. Where do moral values come from? Can moral claims be objectively true? How do we resolve disagreements between fundamentally different ethical systems? These are the questions of meta-ethics, and understanding them gives debaters a powerful edge.\n\nMeta-ethics is distinct from normative ethics (which tells us what we ought to do) and applied ethics (which applies ethical principles to specific situations). Meta-ethics examines the nature, foundations, and methodology of ethics itself. In debate, meta-ethical arguments are used to challenge the very basis of an opponent's moral reasoning, making them extremely difficult to answer if the opponent has not considered these questions.\n\nThis lesson introduces the major meta-ethical positions and shows you how to deploy them strategically in debate. You do not need to be a philosophy major to use these arguments — you just need to understand the core ideas and know when they give you a strategic advantage.",
