        content:
          "One of the most important meta-ethical concepts for debaters is Hume's is-ought problem, also known as the naturalistic fallacy. Hume observed that you cannot logically derive an 'ought' statement (what should be done) from an 'is' statement (what is the case). Just because something is natural, common, or traditional does not mean it ought to be that way. This has enormous implications for debate.\n\nIn practice, debaters constantly commit the is-ought fallacy without realizing it. They argue: 'Countries have always prioritized sovereignty, therefore they should continue to do so.' Or: 'Markets naturally produce inequality, therefore inequality is acceptable.' In both cases, a factual observation is being treated as a moral justification. If you can identify this fallacy in your opponent's arguments, you can seriously damage their case by pointing out that they have not actually provided a moral reason for their position — only a descriptive one.\n\nTo avoid this fallacy yourself, make sure your arguments always include an explicit normative bridge — a moral principle that connects your factual claims to your evaluative conclusions. Instead of arguing 'this policy will increase GDP, therefore it is good,' say 'this policy will increase GDP, and increasing GDP is good because it reduces poverty, which causes suffering that we have a moral obligation to alleviate.' The additional steps connect the factual claim to a moral conclusion through explicit ethical reasoning.\n\nThe is-ought problem also creates strategic opportunities. When your opponent's entire case rests on empirical claims without normative justification, you can argue that they have not given the judge any reason to care about those facts. Facts alone do not tell us what to do — we need values to interpret them, and whoever controls the values controls the debate.",
