        content:
          "**Mistake 1: Going Too Deep into Philosophy**\nMeta-ethics is powerful, but you can lose a round by making it too abstract. Most judges are not philosophy professors, and a debate that devolves into an argument about whether moral facts supervene on natural properties will lose the audience. Use meta-ethical concepts strategically — deploy them to win specific arguments, but always connect them back to the concrete issues in the debate. The best meta-ethical debaters make complex ideas feel simple and relevant.\n\n**Mistake 2: Nihilistic Overreach**\nSome debaters deploy moral anti-realism as a blunt weapon, arguing that since no moral claims are objectively true, nothing matters. This is rarely persuasive because judges intuitively believe that the debate should matter and that some outcomes are better than others. Even if you win the meta-ethical point, nihilism gives the judge no reason to vote for you. Instead, use anti-realism surgically to challenge specific moral claims your opponent makes, then provide your own pragmatic or constructivist basis for why your side is preferable.\n\n**Mistake 3: Confusing Meta-Ethics with Normative Ethics**\nMeta-ethics is about the nature of ethics; normative ethics is about what we ought to do. Saying 'utilitarianism is correct' is a normative claim. Saying 'moral claims can be objectively true, and utilitarianism correctly identifies those truths' is a meta-ethical claim. In debate, clearly distinguish which level you are arguing on. If your opponent is making a normative argument and you respond with a meta-ethical one, make sure the judge understands that you are challenging the foundation, not just disagreeing on content.\n\n**Mistake 4: Ignoring the Judge's Moral Intuitions**\nUltimately, the judge decides the round based on their own reasoning. If your meta-ethical argument conflicts with the judge's deeply held moral intuitions (for example, arguing that human rights are social constructions to a judge who believes in natural rights), you may win the argument technically but lose the round. Read your judge and deploy meta-ethics in ways that align with or strategically challenge their likely beliefs.",
