        type: "content",
        title: "Selecting Relevant Current Events",
        content:
          "**Direct Relevance**\nThe strongest current event references are those directly related to the resolution. If you are debating a resolution about climate policy, referencing the latest IPCC report or a recent extreme weather event is directly relevant. These references work because they provide real-world evidence that the judge can independently verify and that directly supports or undermines a claim in the debate. Always prioritize direct relevance over dramatic impact when selecting current events.\n\n**Analogical Relevance**\nSometimes the most useful current events are not directly about the resolution topic but are structurally analogous. For example, if you are debating whether a certain economic policy should be adopted in the United States, you might reference a similar policy recently implemented in another country and its results. Analogical current events are powerful because they provide real-world data about what actually happens when similar policies are tried — but you must clearly explain why the analogy holds.\n\n**Trend Evidence**\nCurrent events can also be used to establish trends that support your arguments about likely future outcomes. Rather than citing a single event, you reference a pattern of recent developments. For example: 'Over the past three years, we have seen increasing frequency of supply chain disruptions — the Suez Canal blockage, the semiconductor shortage, and the recent port strikes all demonstrate that global supply chains are becoming more fragile, which supports our argument for domestic manufacturing investment.' Trend evidence is harder to dismiss than individual anecdotes.\n\n**Timeliness Matters**\nThe more recent the event, the more impact it tends to have. Citing something from last week is more compelling than something from two years ago, because it suggests the issue is actively relevant and that you are staying current. However, do not sacrifice relevance for recency — a perfectly relevant event from six months ago beats a tangentially related event from yesterday.",
