          "**The Opening Hook**\nStarting a speech with a relevant current event immediately grabs the judge's attention and signals that your arguments are grounded in reality. For example: 'Just last month, the European Union passed its landmark AI regulation act, demonstrating that the question of technology governance we are debating today is not theoretical — governments around the world are actively grappling with it.' This technique establishes relevance and authority in your opening seconds.\n\n**The Evidence Supplement**\nCurrent events work powerfully as supplements to traditional debate evidence. After presenting a theoretical argument or reading a piece of evidence, you can reinforce it with a current event: 'Our evidence from Professor Smith argues that sanctions rarely achieve their stated goals. This analysis is confirmed by recent events — despite years of comprehensive sanctions, North Korea's nuclear program has only expanded.' The combination of academic evidence and real-world confirmation is very persuasive.\n\n**The Impact Concretizer**\nAbstract impact claims become far more compelling when connected to current events. Instead of arguing 'economic instability could lead to social unrest,' say 'economic instability leads to social unrest — we saw this just months ago when inflation in Argentina sparked widespread protests that destabilized the government.' Current events transform abstract possibilities into documented realities.\n\n**The Cross-Examination Weapon**\nCurrent events are devastating in cross-examination. If your opponent makes a theoretical claim, you can ask: 'If your framework is correct, how do you explain what happened when [country] implemented exactly the policy you are advocating and experienced [negative outcome]?' This forces the opponent to either engage with inconvenient real-world evidence or look evasive by dismissing documented events.",
