        type: "content",
        title: "Staying Prepared: Building a Current Events Practice",
        content:
          "**Daily News Habits**\nThe best debaters develop daily habits for staying current. Read at least one major news source each day — not just headlines, but full articles that provide context and analysis. Focus on international affairs, economic policy, technology developments, and legal decisions, as these are the areas most frequently relevant to debate resolutions. Even 15 minutes of focused reading per day will dramatically improve your ability to incorporate current events.\n\n**Building a Reference Library**\nKeep a running document or folder where you save articles and notes about current events organized by topic. When a new resolution is announced, you can quickly scan your library for relevant events. This is far more efficient than trying to remember everything you have read. Include the date, source, key facts, and a brief note about how the event might be relevant to debate topics.\n\n**Practice Integration**\nDuring practice rounds, deliberately incorporate current events into your speeches even if it feels forced at first. The skill of smoothly weaving a current event into an argument requires practice — it should feel natural and relevant, not like you are reading a news report. Work on connecting current events to your framework and specific arguments so that the reference adds value rather than just demonstrating that you read the news.\n\n**Pre-Tournament Research**\nBefore each tournament, spend time researching current events specifically related to the resolution topic. Look for recent developments, new data, policy changes, and expert commentary. This targeted research gives you the most relevant and impactful current event references. Pay particular attention to events your opponents are likely to cite so you can prepare responses in advance.",
