        content:
          "**Accuracy Is Non-Negotiable**\nMisrepresenting current events — exaggerating outcomes, omitting key context, or citing events that did not happen as described — is both ethically wrong and strategically dangerous. Judges who know the facts will lose trust in everything else you say. Opponents who catch you misrepresenting an event will use it to attack your credibility on all your arguments. Always ensure your characterization of current events is accurate and defensible.\n\n**Sensitivity to Tragedy**\nSome current events involve human suffering — natural disasters, wars, terrorist attacks, pandemics. Using these events in debate requires sensitivity. Reference them to make substantive points, not to manipulate emotions. Frame your references with appropriate gravity: 'The recent earthquake in Turkey, which killed over 50,000 people, illustrates the critical importance of building code enforcement' is appropriate. Treating tragedies as mere debate ammunition without acknowledging the human dimension is not.\n\n**Avoid Partisan Framing**\nIn debate, you may need to reference politically controversial events. Do so in a way that focuses on facts and policy outcomes rather than partisan talking points. Instead of 'the disastrous policy of Party X,' say 'the policy implemented in 2024 resulted in a 15% increase in unemployment according to Bureau of Labor Statistics data.' Factual framing is both more credible and more appropriate in competitive debate, where the goal is reasoned argumentation, not political advocacy.\n\nUsing current events well is a hallmark of sophisticated debate. It shows you understand that arguments exist in a real-world context and that the policies being debated affect real people. This combination of intellectual rigor and real-world awareness is what distinguishes truly excellent debaters from technically proficient ones.",
