        type: "content",
        title: "Responding to Advanced Theory",
        content:
          "**The Hierarchy of Responses**\nWhen hit with a theory shell, you have several response options that should be deployed in order of priority. First, challenge the Interpretation — argue it is too restrictive, not commonly accepted, or not supported by the resolution's language. Second, deny the Violation — show that your case or behavior actually meets their interpretation. Third, attack the Standards — explain why their standards do not actually justify their interpretation. Fourth, contest the Voters — argue that the violation, even if real, is not severe enough to be a voting issue.\n\n**Counter-Interpretations**\nThe most powerful response to theory is offering your own counter-interpretation that permits your behavior while still maintaining reasonable limits on the topic. A counter-interpretation says: 'We agree that some interpretation is needed, but theirs is too narrow. Under our interpretation, the topic remains limited enough for fair debate while allowing our case.' The key is showing that your counter-interpretation is reasonable — it provides sufficient limits and ground for both sides.\n\n**Reasonability vs. Competing Interpretations**\nThis is one of the most important meta-theory debates. Under 'competing interpretations,' the judge compares both interpretations and votes for whichever is better. Under 'reasonability,' the judge asks whether your interpretation is good enough — if it is reasonable, you win even if theirs is slightly better. Arguing for reasonability is strategically advantageous for the person responding to theory because it lowers the threshold they need to meet.\n\n**The RVI (Reverse Voting Issue)**\nAn RVI argues that because the opponent's theory shell was frivolous or abusive, the judge should vote against them for running it. RVIs are controversial — some judges accept them, others consider them illegitimate. The strongest RVI arguments focus on how the theory shell wasted time and distracted from substantive debate, especially when the alleged violation is trivial. Only run an RVI when the theory shell is genuinely frivolous and your judge is receptive.",
