        type: "content",
        title: "Advanced Theory Shells: Examples",
        content:
          "**Kritik Links as Theory**\nAt the highest levels, the line between theory and critical arguments blurs. Some debaters argue that an opponent's discursive choices in the round — the language they use, the assumptions they make — constitute theoretical violations. For example: 'Their case assumes a Western-centric framework without acknowledging alternative epistemologies. This is a theoretical violation because it limits the types of arguments that can be run in debate, undermining education and inclusivity.' This type of argument bridges theory and critical philosophy.\n\n**Performative Contradictions**\nA performative contradiction occurs when the act of making an argument contradicts the content of that argument. For example, if an opponent argues that debate should prioritize marginalized voices but then uses exclusively privileged-perspective evidence, they have performatively contradicted themselves. Theory shells on performative contradictions are powerful because they demonstrate internal inconsistency that the opponent cannot resolve without fundamentally changing their approach.\n\n**Disclosure Theory**\nAt the national circuit level, disclosure theory argues that teams should reveal their cases online before tournaments to promote preparation equality and educational depth. A disclosure theory shell argues: 'Interpretation: All debaters should disclose their cases on the relevant wiki at least 30 minutes before the round. Violation: They did not disclose. Standards: Non-disclosure undermines negative preparation, reduces clash depth, and creates unfair information asymmetry. Voters: Fairness and education.' Disclosure theory is highly judge-dependent — some judges strongly support it, others reject it entirely.\n\n**Argument Quality Theory**\nSome advanced shells argue that running knowingly bad arguments violates debate norms. The shell claims: 'Debaters have an obligation to run arguments they genuinely believe are true, because running arguments you know are false undermines the educational and truth-seeking purpose of debate.' This is controversial but can be effective against opponents who clearly do not believe their own arguments and are running them purely for strategic advantage.",
