        title: "Review: Framework Competition",
        content:
          "**Core Concept**\nFramework debates occur when both sides present different criteria for evaluating the round. The debater who wins the framework question typically wins the round because they control how all other arguments are assessed. Common framework clashes include utilitarianism vs. deontology, security vs. liberty, and pragmatism vs. principle.\n\n**Key Strategies**\nFour primary strategies exist for winning framework debates: demonstrating superior ground (your framework enables fairer debate), showing real-world applicability (your framework reflects actual decision-making), arguing logical priority (your framework must be resolved first), and framework inclusivity (your framework encompasses the opponent's values plus more). Meta-weighing provides judges with explicit criteria for choosing between frameworks, which is essential because leaving the choice to the judge's discretion is risky.\n\n**Advanced Technique: Conditional Framework Arguments**\nThe gold standard is showing you win under both frameworks. This eliminates the judge's need to resolve the framework question because your side prevails regardless. However, this requires genuine strength under both frameworks — a weak conditional argument can undermine your primary framework by suggesting lack of commitment.\n\n**Connection to Other Concepts**\nFramework debates connect directly to meta-ethics (which examines the foundations of the ethical systems underlying frameworks), to theory (where topicality and other shells can affect which frameworks are legitimate), and to current events (which can demonstrate real-world validity of a framework). Recognizing these connections allows you to build mutually reinforcing arguments across multiple levels.",
