        content:
          "**Hypotheticals Recap**\nHypothetical arguments test logical implications, expose weaknesses, and illustrate abstract principles. The four main types are reductio ad absurdum (taking arguments to their logical extreme), analogical hypotheticals (drawing structural parallels), counterfactuals (what would have happened), and thought experiments (isolating variables to test principles). Effective hypotheticals are relevant, logically consistent, and concrete. Responses include challenging relevance, accepting and distinguishing, flipping, and constructing counter-hypotheticals.\n\n**Meta-Ethics Recap**\nMeta-ethics examines the foundations of ethics itself — where moral values come from and whether moral claims can be objectively true. The major positions are moral realism (objective moral facts exist), anti-realism (they do not), relativism (moral truths are context-dependent), and constructivism (moral facts are built through rational agreement). Key practical concepts include the is-ought problem (you cannot derive moral claims from factual observations) and the argument from moral uncertainty (we should minimize catastrophic moral error).\n\n**How They Connect**\nHypotheticals and meta-ethics work together powerfully. Thought experiments are a primary tool of meta-ethical argumentation — they test whether ethical principles hold under specific conditions. The is-ought problem is often exposed through hypothetical reasoning ('If your logic is correct, then in this scenario, we would have to accept that...'). And meta-ethical frameworks determine what kinds of hypotheticals are relevant — a consequentialist cares about outcome-based hypotheticals, while a deontologist cares about duty-based ones.\n\nUnderstanding how these tools interact allows you to construct more sophisticated arguments and identify opportunities your opponents miss.",
