        content:
          "**Theory Shell Structure**\nAdvanced theory shells have four parts: Interpretation (precise statement of the debate norm), Violation (how the opponent broke it), Standards (multiple independent reasons the norm matters — limits, ground, education, fairness), and Voters (why the violation should determine the round outcome). Precision in each component makes shells harder to evade, and layered standards create resilience.\n\n**Strategic Deployment**\nJudge preferences are the most important factor in theory strategy. Research your judge before every round. Distinguish genuine violations from strategic theory — judges increasingly penalize frivolous shells. Layer theory with substance using dual-path strategies: spend 30-40% of time on theory and 60-70% on substance. Consider conditional theory framing: present theory as a secondary path to victory rather than your primary strategy.\n\n**Responding to Theory**\nRespond in priority order: challenge the Interpretation, deny the Violation, attack the Standards, contest the Voters. Counter-interpretations are the most powerful response — they permit your behavior while maintaining reasonable limits. Argue for the reasonability standard (your interpretation only needs to be 'good enough') rather than competing interpretations (which requires your interpretation to be better). Use RVIs selectively against genuinely frivolous shells.\n\n**Advanced Concepts**\nPerformative contradictions, disclosure theory, kritik links as theory, and argument quality theory represent the cutting edge of theory debate. Each has specific applications and limitations. The key insight is that theory is not separate from the rest of debate — it interacts with frameworks, meta-ethics, and substantive arguments in ways that create opportunities for strategic advantage.",
